---
intent: >
  Fix eight visual inconsistencies found during a Playwright-based audit
  at 1280px, 768px, and 375px — connector/step coordination, section
  spacing rhythm, comparison card contrast, blockquote emphasis, footer
  CTA weight, and CostStrip visual anchoring — without adding new beats,
  new navigation, or marketing chrome.
---

## Plan

### Step 1: Normalize section spacing rhythm

Files:
- `src/components/LandingPage/InstallHero/index.tsx`
- `src/components/LandingPage/CostStrip/index.tsx`
- `src/components/LandingPage/HowItWorks/index.tsx`
- `src/components/LandingPage/VsRulesPacks/index.tsx`
- `src/components/LandingPage/HallucinationEvidence/index.tsx`
- `src/components/shared/InstallFooter/index.tsx`

- [x] Establish a two-tier spacing system: `py-20` for the hero (it earns
      extra breathing room as the entry point), `py-16` for all five
      content/mechanism sections (CostStrip, HowItWorks, VsRulesPacks,
      HallucinationEvidence, InstallFooter). Change CostStrip from `py-14`
      to `py-16` and InstallFooter from `py-10` to `py-16`. Leave
      InstallHero at `py-20` and the three middle beats at `py-16`
      (already correct).

Spec trace: The spec mandates five beats in exact order with no
decorative interstitials. Consistent vertical rhythm reinforces that
these are peers in a single scroll path, not a grab-bag of unrelated
sections. Playbook component architecture: spacing belongs to the page
layout, but since these are self-contained sections with their own
vertical padding, normalizing at the component level is acceptable when
no orchestrator-level spacing wrapper exists.

---

### Step 2: Add a visual anchor to CostStrip

File: `src/components/LandingPage/CostStrip/index.tsx`

- [x] Add a short label above the paragraph — a `<p>` element styled as
      an uppercase monospace section label (matching the existing pattern
      used in HowItWorks "brain — shared infrastructure" and VsRulesPacks
      "Rules packs" / "AIDE" labels). Text: something like
      "The specialist hire" or "What you replace" — a terse anchor that
      tells the reader what category they are looking at. Keep it to 2-4
      words. Do not add a full `<h2>` heading — the CostStrip is a
      transitional beat, not a named section.
- [x] Increase border contrast from `border-zinc-800` to `border-zinc-700`
      on top and bottom borders so the strip reads as a distinct visual
      unit against the `bg-zinc-950` page background.

Spec trace: The spec defines CostStrip as beat 2, "Specialist cost
strip." It ships two figures with inline attribution and a terse
conclusion. A label anchors the strip visually without adding a new
beat or expanding its content. The border bump keeps it from looking
orphaned. No heading hierarchy change — the spec does not give CostStrip
a heading in the Good Examples section; the label is decorative/navigational.

