## Decisions

### D1: Two-tier spacing (py-20 hero / py-16 everything else) over uniform

The hero earns extra vertical breathing room because it is the entry
point and contains the most content (headline, subhead, JSON code block,
three-step sequence, troubleshooting callout). Making all sections py-20
would waste vertical space on shorter sections like CostStrip and
HallucinationEvidence. Making all sections py-16 would cramp the hero.
Two tiers create a clear hierarchy: hero is the arrival, everything else
is the scroll path.

### D2: CostStrip gets a label, not a heading

The spec's Good Examples section shows the CostStrip as a paragraph with
inline figures — no heading. Adding a full `<h2>` would elevate it to
the same heading hierarchy as "How it works" and "Not a rules pack,"
which it does not deserve — it is a transitional beat, not a named
section. An uppercase monospace label (matching the existing pattern in
HowItWorks and VsRulesPacks) anchors it visually without inflating its
heading rank.

### D3: Flex-based connector over calculated height

The HowItWorks connector lines currently use a fixed `h-12` which breaks
when annotation text wraps to different heights across breakpoints. A
flex-grow approach lets the connector fill available space dynamically.
This is pure CSS, no JS, and follows the playbook rule of using Tailwind
over runtime calculation. Alternative considered: setting min-height on
all steps — rejected because it wastes space on short annotations and
doesn't adapt to font-size changes.

### D4: Comparison card contrast via border + background, not color accents

The spec demands "engineering-credible aesthetic" and the bad examples
warn against marketing chrome. Using a green/red color scheme for the
comparison cards would read as a marketing technique. Instead, contrast
comes from the zinc scale: the Rules packs card stays muted (lower
border, lower background opacity) while the AIDE card steps up in both.
The `+` markers may use a subtle emerald tone at implementor discretion,
but the cards themselves stay within the zinc palette.

### D5: Finding 8 (brand mark) rejected per spec

Adding a brand mark above the fold on mobile pushes the install command
further down, directly violating the spec's first desired outcome. The
spec explicitly forbids a header and warns against any element that
creates an off-ramp before the install block. The h1 headline serves as
the identity anchor. If brand recognition becomes a concern, it belongs
in the meta tags (og:image, favicon), not in the DOM above the hero.

### D6: Footer CTA — CodeBlock reuse preferred over custom container

The spec says the final install block should be "identical to the hero's
install block." Reusing the existing `CodeBlock` component from
`@/components/shared/CodeBlock` is the most faithful implementation.
If CodeBlock is too large/verbose for the footer context, the implementor
may use a styled container that visually matches — but CodeBlock reuse
is the first choice per the spec's "identical" language.

### D7: No new files created

All changes are modifications to existing component files. No new
helpers, no new shared components, no new folders. The visual fixes
are styling adjustments within existing component boundaries. This
follows the progressive disclosure principle: the folder structure
should not change when the visual treatment changes.
